ALREADY THIS IS THERE WHAT TO DO?

You've got a great start! You have a Maven project structure (I see that pom.xml), your Java files, and a blank Jenkinsfile.

To complete the Dynamic Discount System, you need to fill in that Jenkinsfile and your Java code so they actually do the work.

1. The Code (App.java)
Open App.java and replace its content with the discount logic. This is the "brain" of your system.

Java
package com.example; // Make sure this matches your folder structure

public class App {
    public double calculateDiscount(double price, String season, int inventory) {
        double discount = 0.0;
        
        if (season.equalsIgnoreCase("Summer")) discount += 0.10;
        if (inventory > 100) discount += 0.20; // High stock = bigger discount
        
        return price * (1 - discount);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Discount System Active!");
    }
}
2. The Test (AppTest.java)
Open AppTest.java. This fulfills the "JUnit tests" requirement from your assignment.

Java
package com.example;
import static org.junit.Assert.assertEquals;
import org.junit.Test;

public class AppTest {
    @Test
    public void testDiscount() {
        App app = new App();
        // $100 price, Summer, 150 items should give 30% off ($70)
        assertEquals(70.0, app.calculateDiscount(100.0, "Summer", 150), 0.01);
    }
}
3. The Automation (Jenkinsfile)
Now, go back to that Jenkinsfile in your screenshot and paste this. This tells Jenkins how to build, test, and "Dockerize" your app automatically.

Groovy
pipeline {
    agent any
    stages {
        stage('Compile') {
            steps {
                bat 'mvn clean compile' 
            }
        }
        stage('Test') {
            steps {
                bat 'mvn test'
            }
        }
        stage('Docker Build') {
            steps {
                // This creates your image after the tests pass
                bat 'docker build -t discount-app .'
            }
        }
    }
}
4. Create your Dockerfile
You are missing a Dockerfile in your explorer. Create a new file named Dockerfile (no extension) in that main folder and paste:

Dockerfile
FROM openjdk:17-jdk-slim
COPY target/*.jar app.jar
ENTRYPOINT ["java", "-jar", "/app.jar"]
