NOW WHAT SHLD I DO ?

You have successfully built your Docker image! Now you need to fulfill the final and most "pro" part of your assignment: Kubernetes.

In the industry, we don't just run one container; we use Kubernetes (K8s) to manage hundreds of them. Since you are a beginner, we will use a Manifest file (a YAML file) to tell Kubernetes how to run your discount system.

☸️ Step 1: Create the Kubernetes Deployment
In your discount-system folder in VS Code, create a new file named deployment.yaml.

Paste this code inside:

YAML
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: discount-deployment
spec:
  replicas: 2 # This tells K8s to run TWO copies of your app for safety
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: discount-system
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: discount-system
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: discount-app
        image: discount-app # This uses the image you just built
        imagePullPolicy: Never # Tells K8s to look on your computer, not the internet
🚀 Step 2: Apply to Kubernetes
To run this, you need to make sure Kubernetes is enabled in your Docker Desktop settings.

Open Docker Desktop.

Click the Settings (gear icon) -> Kubernetes.

Check "Enable Kubernetes" and click Apply & Restart. (Wait until the little boat icon in the bottom corner turns green).

Once it's ready, run this in your VS Code Terminal:

PowerShell
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
📊 Step 3: Verify it's Working
Run this command to see your "Fleet" of discount apps running:

PowerShell
kubectl get pods
What you should see: Two rows showing discount-deployment-... with a status of Running.

✅ The Final Checklist
To finish your assignment completely, you should now have:

Java Code: DiscountCalculator.java (Logic complete).

JUnit Test: DiscountTest.java (Passed).

Docker: Dockerfile (Built and Run).

Kubernetes: deployment.yaml (Applied and Running).

CI/CD: Your Jenkinsfile from earlier (which ties it all together).

Do you see the "Running" status when you type kubectl get pods? If yes, you are officially a DevOps beginner!

