▶️ Step 3: Run the Container
Now, type this command to see your code work:

PowerShell
docker run discount-app
Expected Result: You should see Final Price: 70.0 printed in the terminal.

📋 Why you were "lagging":
Broken Commands: Docker needs specific words like FROM, COPY, and WORKDIR. Your file had DIR and mpile, which are not real Docker commands.

Missing Compilation: Java files (.java) need to be compiled into classes (.class) before they can run. The javac command in the Dockerfile handles this.

Try running those two commands in your terminal now. Does it show "Final Price: 70.0" or do you see a red error message?

NOPE NEXT STEO

If your Docker build and run worked, you have officially containerized your app! Now we move to the final stage of the project: Kubernetes (K8s).

In your previous tasks, you ran a single container. In the real world, we use Kubernetes to run many copies of the same container so that if one crashes, the others keep working.

☸️ Step 1: Create the Kubernetes Manifest
In your discount-system folder, create a new file named deployment.yaml.

Paste this exact code inside:

YAML
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: discount-system-deploy
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: discount
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: discount
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: discount-container
        image: discount-app
        imagePullPolicy: Never
🚀 Step 2: Push to Kubernetes
Open your Terminal at the bottom of VS Code and run this command:

PowerShell
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
Wait! If you get an error saying "kubectl is not recognized," make sure you have enabled Kubernetes in Docker Desktop Settings (Settings > Kubernetes > Enable).

📊 Step 3: Verify the Deployment
To see if Kubernetes is actually running your code, type:

PowerShell
kubectl get pods
What you want to see: You should see two rows starting with discount-system-deploy-... and the status should say Running.

📝 Summary of what you just did:
Java: Created the logic.

Docker: Created the image (discount-app).

Kubernetes: Created a "Deployment" that manages two copies (replicas) of your app.

Run kubectl get pods and let me know if they show up as "Running"!

The errors in your terminal show that Docker Desktop is not currently running, and because Docker is off, Kubernetes is also off.

When you see failed to connect to the docker API and connection actively refused, it means the "engine" that runs these tools is asleep.

🛠️ The Fix: Restart the Engines
1. Open Docker Desktop
Find the Docker Desktop app on your computer and open it.

Look at the bottom left corner of the Docker Desktop window.

You need to wait until the little whale icon turns Green and says "Engine Running."

2. Turn on Kubernetes
Once Docker is green, check the Kubernetes status (next to the whale). If it's not green:

Go to Settings (gear icon) → Kubernetes.

Click "Enable Kubernetes" and then "Apply & Restart."

This can take 2–3 minutes. Don't run commands until it's finished!

🚀 Try the Commands Again
Once everything is green in Docker Desktop, go back to your VS Code terminal and run these:

First, Build (since the previous one failed):

PowerShell
docker build -t discount-app .
Second, Apply to Kubernetes:

PowerShell
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
Third, Check if it worked:

PowerShell
kubectl get pods
💡 Why did it say "Connection Refused"?
Think of Docker Desktop like a power station. If the power station is off, your lights (Docker commands) and your appliances (Kubernetes) won't work. The error message is just your computer saying, "I'm trying to talk to Docker, but nobody is answering!"

Is Docker Desktop showing a green status now?

next

Since you've run the apply command, the final step in a real DevOps workflow is to expose your application so you can actually see it running, and then verify everything is healthy.

1. Expose the Service
Currently, your pods are running inside a private network. To see the output, you need to create a "Service."

In VS Code, create a file named service.yaml and paste this:

YAML
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: discount-service
spec:
  type: NodePort
  selector:
    app: discount
  ports:
    - port: 80
      targetPort: 80
      nodePort: 30001
Then run this in your terminal:

PowerShell
kubectl apply -f service.yaml
2. The Final Verification (The "Proof")
Run these two commands to take your final "Success" screenshots:

Check Pods:

PowerShell
kubectl get pods
Wait until they say STATUS: Running.

Check Service:

PowerShell
kubectl get service discount-service
3. Check the Logs
Because this is a Java console app (not a website), it runs the calculation and then finishes. To see the "Final Price: 70.0" output from Kubernetes, you have to look at the logs of one of your pods.

Find a pod name from your get pods list (e.g., discount-system-deploy-xyz) and run:

PowerShell
kubectl logs [YOUR_POD_NAME_HERE]
